Introduction¶

The dataset has been taken from https://www.kaggle.com/abcsds/pokemon and included the following columns: Name, Type 1, Type 2, Total : sum of the rest, HP : hit points, Attack, Defence, Sp.Attk. Special Attack, Sp.Def : Special Deffence, Speed, Generation,and Legancy

#standarize not binary columns
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
col_names = ["HP", "Attack", "Defense", "Sp. Atk", "Sp. Def", "Speed"]
features = pokemon_copy[col_names]
scaler = StandardScaler().fit(features.values)
features = scaler.transform(features.values)

pokemon_copy[col_names] = features
#one hot encoding for type 1 and generation columns
pokemon_copy = pd.get_dummies(pokemon_copy, columns=['Type 1'], drop_first = True)
pokemon_copy = pd.get_dummies(pokemon_copy, columns=['Generation'], drop_first = True)

#replace binary columns with 1 and 0
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
le = LabelEncoder()
pokemon_copy["Legendary"] = le.fit_transform(pokemon_copy["Legendary"])
pokemon_copy

Dimension Reduction¶

I will use PCA for dimension reduction. I plot the PCA features variance to select the number of components to keep. I decided to keep the first 5 based on the plot below.

In [6]:
pokemon_numpy = pokemon_copy.to_numpy()
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
pca = PCA()
pca.fit(pokemon_numpy)
Out[6]:
PCA()
In [7]:
features_all = range(pca.n_components_)
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 11})
plt.bar(features_all, pca.explained_variance_)
plt.xticks(features_all)
plt.ylabel('variance')
plt.xlabel('PCA feature')
plt.show()
In [8]:
pca_5 = PCA(n_components=5)
pca_5.fit(pokemon_numpy)
Out[8]:
PCA(n_components=5)
In [9]:
#transform data to 5 variables
transformed = pca_5.transform(pokemon_numpy)
print(transformed.shape)

(800, 5)

Group Pokemons in Clusters¶

I will use Kmeans to create clusters- groups of pokemons with common characteristics

In [10]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
#find the best k
ks = range(1, 15)
inertias = []
 
for k in ks:
    # Create a KMeans instance with k clusters: model
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
     
    # Fit model to samples
    model.fit(transformed)
     
    # Append the inertia to the list of inertias
    inertias.append(model.inertia_)
 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt    
# Plot ks vs inertias
plt.plot(ks, inertias, '-o')
plt.xlabel('number of clusters, k')
plt.ylabel('inertia')
plt.xticks(ks)
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 25})
plt.show()

I will select k=3. I add a column to the initial dataset with the predicted labels (groups)

In [11]:
#create the kmeans model, fit the model
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3)
kmeans.fit(transformed)
 
#make the predictions
labels = kmeans.predict(transformed)
In [12]:
pokemon_labeled = pokemon.copy()
pokemon_labeled["cluster"] = labels
pokemon_labeled["cluster"] = pokemon_labeled["cluster"].astype("category")
pokemon_labeled

Anomaly Detection¶

Finally, I want to detect possible anomalies using Local outlier factor. For this I will fit the PCA transformed 5 feature dataset

In [29]:
from sklearn.neighbors import LocalOutlierFactor as lof
clf = lof()
y_pred_ad = clf.fit_predict(transformed)
In [30]:
#create dataframe with PCA features, cluster and anomaly labels
pca_df = pd.DataFrame(transformed, columns = ["PCA feature 0", "PCA feature 1", "PCA feature 2", "PCA feature 3","PCA feature 4"])
pca_df["cluster"] = labels
pca_df["anomaly"] = y_pred_ad
pca_df

Summary¶

In this project, I explored a pokemon dataset and group pokemon in groups with common characteristics. Then, I explore the data and plot some summary insights. Finally, I detect possible anomalies in the dataset.
